    "As a result, the sub-synchronous currents increase, and this is called as the induction generator effect (IGE) [19,41].The corresponding rotor resistance at a Subsynchronous frequency is (1)f er = f 0 √ X c X t (2) S SSR = f er - f 0 f er (3) R eq = R S SSRFig.",
    "1 Turbine-Generator System with a Series-Compensated Line [36] If f er < f o, the resistance becomes negative, indicating that the damping is negative, and an overdamped oscillation of the voltage and current is observed [19].ii.",
    "Torsional Interaction (TI) Synchronous generator rotor generates oscillation frequency fen because of torsional frequency f n at which armature voltage is produced at sub-synchronous frequency range.",
    "The amplitude of oscillation is given by f en = f o -f n. If this voltage component frequency ( f en) coincides with the electrical resonating frequency of the system, the electromagnetic torque generated will contribute to the torsional oscillation, which is evident in the mechanical system.",
    "In general, the torsional oscillation is close to the electrical resonant frequency [42].Negative damping from the IGE and TI causes generator self-excitation at Subsynchronous frequencies, involving the interaction between the electrical network and the mechanical system of the turbine generator [43]."
  ]
